{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:20:18.851013", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — network assessment and findings\n\nSummary / executive view\n- Two user hosts (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1) are not receiving IP addresses (no IPv4 configured) and therefore are effectively offline from a user perspective.\n- There is a routing/forwarding break between the server-farm subnet 10.200.0.0/24 and the backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24. Traffic from the backends (20.200.0.0/24) reaches the load balancer but fails to reach most 10.200.0.0 hosts and infrastructure (DNS/DHCP) — and replies fail to get back. The result is that backend servers are isolated from 10.200.0.0 clients.\n- Internal 10.200.0.0/24 hosts (web_server_0..3, dns_server, dhcp_server, load_balancer eth0) can talk to each other normally; backend hosts (20.200.0.2..4) can talk to each other and to the load_balancer on 20.200.0.1 — but cross-subnet communication between 10.200 and 20.200 is not working end-to-end.\n\nObserved anomalies (with supporting evidence)\n1) Hosts have no IPv4 address (DHCP failure)\n- host_1_1_1_1 ifconfig / ip addr: eth0 is UP but contains no \"inet\" entry (no IPv4 assigned). ip_route is empty.\n- host_2_1_1_1 shows the same (UP link, no IPv4).\n- Reachability checks from these hosts to other hosts/networks returned status \"unknown\" — they did not participate in pings because they lack IPs.\n- Implication: client-hosts cannot access any services or resolve names because they are not receiving DHCP configuration.\n\n2) Backend (20.200.0.0/24) ↔ Server-farm (10.200.0.0/24) routing is broken / asymmetric\n- Reachability matrix:\n  - backend_web_* -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7) : OK (0% loss).\n  - backend_web_* -> dns_server (10.200.0.2) : 100% loss.\n  - backend_web_* -> dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) : 100% loss.\n  - backend_web_* -> web_server_0..3 (10.200.0.x) : 100% loss in most cases.\n  - web_server_* -> web_server_*/dns/dhcp : OK (internal 10.200 connectivity fine).\n  - web_server_3 -> backend_web_0: 100% loss (shows unreachability from 10.200→20.200 in some directions as well).\n- load_balancer sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1 and iptables policies ACCEPT — load_balancer is capable of routing/forwarding locally.\n- load_balancer interfaces: eth0 = 10.200.0.7/24, eth1 = 20.200.0.1/24 — it is the gateway for 20.200 hosts and is directly on the 10.200 segment as well.\n- server_access_router (the router for 10.200.0.0/24) OSPF / routing:\n  - router server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 as directly connected and only the links to the OSPF backbone; there is no route to 20.200.0.0/24.\n  - FRR configs show server_access_router advertising/connected only for 10.200.0.0/24 and its point-to-point link; no 20.200 network is visible in the routing table.\n- Interpretation of asymmetry: load_balancer can forward packets from 20.200 hosts onto the 10.200 bus directly (it has an address on 10.200) and so initial packets toward 10.200 targets may reach them, but replies from 10.200 hosts go to their default gateway (server_access_router). The server_access_router does not have a route back to 20.200.0.0/24 (because 20.200 is neither directly connected nor learned via OSPF), so replies are dropped — causing 100% loss as observed. This is classic asymmetric routing / missing route advertisement.\n\nLocalized components likely implicated\n- DHCP service path for user hosts\n  - The hosts' NICs are up but they have no IPv4. The DHCP server (10.200.0.8) is present and reachable from 10.200 servers; the problem is likely in the DHCP relay/forwarding function at the distribution/access layer (router_dist_1_1 and/or router_dist_2_1 or DHCP-relay function on the distribution/router devices or relay agent configuration on switches). Evidence: DHCP server is active and reachable from 10.200 servers, but the user hosts (on subnets 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) never obtained leases.\n  - The link-level connectivity between hosts and access switches is UP (eth0 shows UP), so physical/link layer is OK. The failure is at DHCP request delivery/response (relay) or at client-side DHCP client step.\n- Routing between 10.200.0.0/24 and 20.200.0.0/24\n  - load_balancer (dual-homed) and backend_web_* (20.200.x) are on a separate network not advertised into OSPF (no OSPF/route advertisement for 20.200).\n  - server_access_router does not have a route to 20.200.0.0/24 (not learned via OSPF and not statically configured), so return traffic from 10.200 hosts to 20.200 is lost.\n  - The problem is localized to missing routing information for 20.200.0.0/24 in the network routing domain — either the load_balancer is not injecting/advertising 20.200 into OSPF, or the ingress router (server_access_router) is not configured with a route to 20.200 (no static or OSPF-learned route).\n\nProbable root causes (based on collected evidence)\n1) DHCP relay/configuration missing or non-functional at distribution/access layer\n- User hosts have no IP addresses though DHCP server exists and is functional for servers inside 10.200.\n- The hosts' NICs are up, so DHCP broadcast frames are not being relayed to the central DHCP server (or replies are not returned). The DHCP-relay agent(s) on distribution routers or access switches are the logical place that would cause this symptom if misconfigured or down.\n\n2) 20.200.0.0/24 is not part of the routed OSPF domain (no route advertisement), causing asymmetric routing and blackholing between 10.200 and 20.200\n- The load_balancer and backends use the load_balancer as their gateway (20.200 default), but the rest of the network (server_access_router and OSPF domain) does not know how to reach 20.200, so return traffic fails.\n- This results in the backend tier being effectively inaccessible to user/10.200 hosts (and to infrastructure services on 10.200), except for the load_balancer itself which is multi-homed.\n\nImpact summary\n- User devices: no IPv4 addresses → no network access, cannot reach DNS, web, or any services.\n- Application/service connectivity: backend web servers (20.200) cannot be reached by hosts in 10.200 (end-to-end service failure). From within server-farm (10.200) services can talk to each other, and load_balancer is reachable.\n- DNS/DHCP central services are reachable from 10.200 servers, but not from backend hosts (20.200) and not from unconfigured user hosts.\n\nKey evidence excerpts\n- host_1_1_1_1 ip output: eth0 has no inet address (no DHCP lease).\n- host_2_1_1_1 ip output: same.\n- Reachability: backend_web_* -> dns_server/dhcp_server/web_servers = 100% packet loss in many cases.\n- load_balancer: eth0 10.200.0.7, eth1 20.200.0.1, net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1.\n- server_access_router routing table: shows 10.200.0.0/24 connected, but no route for 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nConclusion\n- Two separate but related issues identified:\n  1) DHCP provisioning failure for access hosts (likely DHCP-relay or relay-config issue at distribution/access layer) — localizes to distribution/access devices or relay configuration.\n  2) Missing routing for backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24 in the routing domain (no advertisement/route on server_access_router and OSPF) — localizes to load_balancer (which is not injecting/participating in routing) and/or server_access_router (no static/OSPF route toward 20.200).\n- Both problems cause significant service impact: clients without IPs; and even if they had addresses, the backend tier would still be unreachable from general clients due to routing asymmetry.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Gather additional concrete artifacts to further narrow the DHCP-relay failure (e.g., check router_dist_* for DHCP-relay configuration, or packet captures on an access interface).\n- Show exact OSPF route tables on server_access_router + core routers to confirm the absence of 20.200 in the routing domain (we've shown server_access_router already).\n- Test targeted pings/traces to demonstrate asymmetric path (e.g., traceroutes from backend → 10.200 and 10.200 → backend) to further confirm return-path drops.\n\n(Per your instruction I have not included remediation steps; this report focuses on detection, localization and root-cause identification.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 15387, "output_tokens": 4751, "total_tokens": 20138, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 14976}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2624}}}
